sentence: A quick check-in with the list of stocks making new highs on Tuesday showed that Align Technology ( ALGN ), Salesforce.com ( CRM ) and Microchip Technologies ( MCHP ) remained within their 5% buy zones.

[ibd-display-video id=2382612 width=50 float=left autostart=true] Footwear brand Skechers ( SKX ), meanwhile, is also holding within buy range above a 39.81 buy point and with a big estimate looming for its Q4 earnings.
Align is the innovator that created Invisalign braces - clear plastic alternatives to the traditional wire and chrome torture regimen for straightening crooked teeth.
The stock gained 161% in February through December, when it started its current pattern.
Shares crept past the 266.51 buy point in modest trade on Jan. 16.
The moves marked a buy opportunity, but stopped well short of a solid breakout .
The fact that it is a third-stage base suggests it would be smart to pyramid into the position, with an eye out for volume to kick in to verify the breakout .
The buy zone extends to 279.83.
Salesforce is a leader in cloud-based software applications, focused on human relations management programs.
The stock topped its buy point in moderate trade, then climbed in seven of the past eight sessions.
Salesforce has cleared three bases since August.
But the current base remains a first-stage pattern.
This gives it a bit more leeway than the later-stage Align.
It's worth noting that Salesforce's relative strength line is somewhat less perky than Align's, although its Accumulation/Distribution Rating is solid at a B-.
Plus, Salesforce and Align both show strong up/down volume ratio readings of 1.4 and 1.3, respectively.
(See both at IBD Stock Checkup .)
Salesforce earnings are expected to hold up at a 29% growth rate across fiscal 2019 (through January that year), although projections for the pending January quarter call for a soft 19% advance.
Microchip Technologies remains in a buy range through 100.82, after clearing its 96.02 buy point in breakout-worthy trade on Jan. 17.
Volume ran solidly higher for two straight sessions following the breakout, giving the breakout added confirmation.
The base is only a second-stage structure, and the stock's up/down volume ratio and Accumulation/Distribution Rating are healthy, at B+ and 1.6, respectively.
After the close, however, Microchip shares were back near their buy point as Texas Instruments ' ( TXN ) quarterly results sparked selling in chip stocks.
A caveat with Microchip is its earnings outlook.
The consensus view calls for a solid 29% EPS gain in the company's fiscal third quarter.
But growth is seen slowing to 7% in fiscal 2019, beginning in its June-ending Q1.
A sharp slowdown in earnings can be a sell sign .
As with many stocks, there are different ways to read Skechers' chart.
The stock formed two bases between February and July of last year.

It barely cleared either buy point, then pulled back for two months, triggering automatic sell rules , before spiking 41% higher after reporting in October its first increase in earnings in six quarters.
The stock formed a five-week flat base atop that rise in October.
It cleared that buy point, at 34.97, in muddled action and weak volume.
Shares also cleared the current buy point in weak trade.
The stock is now up 71% from an October low, with minimal debt and an outlook for earnings acceleration across 2018.
Its relative strength line is rising and chipping out new highs.
Its Accumulation/Distribution Rating is a solid A- and its up/down volume ratio is a positive 1.6.
You would like to see volume support kick in to bolster the gain, in order to confirm that institutional investors are backing the stock's turnaround.
That could easily come if the company hits its marks in its fourth-quarter results.
Analysts expect a 225% surge in earnings, which would mark Skechers' strongest year-over-year growth in any quarter since June 2014.
The company has not yet announced a reporting date.
